e’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":8,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Sutton was born in 1216, in Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England. She had at least 1 son with William de Sutton. She died in 1250, in her hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1216–1250":"1216–1250","1217–1267":"1217–1267","1208–1264":"1208–1264","1240–1279":"1240–1279","1239–1303":"1239–1303","1239":"1239","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1303":"1303","1224":"1224","1279":"1279","1267":"1267","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1208":"1208","Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England":"Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England